[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating SecurityExceptions**\n\nI’m encountering a potential SecurityException due to custom provider class package access in version 4.1.0. While tests cover the string-configured provider path, it uses a default factory class, not arbitrary ones. A dynamic-access call is still executed, but under new JDK requirements, arbitrary classes can't be accessed. Should I add an assertion test for custom factory rejection? It might help document new behavior, but that could complicate things without needing to fix failures. I need to clarify how properties are cleaned up as well.\n\n**Assessing Factory Backed Type Issues**\n\nI’m looking into the \"FactoryBackedBoundType\" test, which is no longer aligned with the JAXBContextFactory implementation by name. The ServiceLoaderUtilTest does cover the `instantiatesProviderClassByName`, but I need to ensure that the `ContextFinder.instantiateProviderIfNecessary` dynamic-access section is also covered. It seems that direct service objects don’t instantiate `ProviderIfNecessary` unless through an OSGI path. I need to check if the OSGI context path utilizes the `FactoryBackedContextFactory` and look into the org.glassfish stub next.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_051d1c9ae9fb9fd50169f6739fbb188195bd80c97b39d46c39\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9nOveIWwIPXqjti5hpxo3sSNxHdw4ydUJiZWT-73TbW6At1Bj9g2hQs6VuR6ORCoFK1RYwyaxDmBO7TWWRIIZH_DOYg71ysd8pJ3q4MTZVMuv0FY7RYCQt9hrvfgoUdadlMTdpW3lqPKOHdwQ-W2lMY6CvyqSAwnVtyjekE-Tm6tqNGPchy2XURnTIah7byqKn_jNWukP11ksfl7KvBaLba2Hft4qfY_rN6x3QTjCx0X9ZTdKtGtT3Ml-6e5aObPMeejrWIFjy6LeHG7edd3PnhxYxM_B2IxJPoELH_Nl2supTEUPEUlq0ix1wFLo34ZE-Q97Ka9J_aAFmoQtP_jHK1lzdMsp4yyE4pJmm83rF8j0VCuC96JSeBDXBrrfQN5jdjEuTQPi4sQEHAXl-Iz3_e-KRnWVDdUBEmQ74QyiNa7Oo9i0ybqLTp1bm55ELZTKWRa_sbW6FGre5g-lvaCvx2Q8K_BTuMSV1jmr0Pd-pNq4u5dzv2UqfnPp6r1wj9TUOHtA4fbnopsRngQI3z0N-twZvepX4SP0ecx8aQVuc-qi